
  - Many of the forms below are quite rare (e.g. `yourselves') but included for completeness.

  - An omission here is the various contractions such as

      I've   she'd   we'll   didn't   couldn't   daren't

    As English communication becomes less formal, these forms are increasingly encountered,
    and a complete list of them is quite long.




           - PRONOUNS FORMS
             - 1st person sing
i              - subject, always in upper case of course
me             - object
my             - possessive adjective
               - the possessive pronoun `mine' is best suppressed, because of the sense of
               - coal-mine etc.
myself         - reflexive
             - 1st person plural
we             - subject
               - the object form `us' is best suppressed, because of `US' so often meaning
               - `United States'
our            - possessive adjective
ours           - possessive pronoun
ourselves      - relexive
             - second person (archaic `thou' forms not included)
you            - subject and object
your           - possessive adjective
yours          - possessive pronoun
yourself       - reflexive (singular)
yourselves     - reflexive (plural)
             - third person singular
he             - subject
him            - object
his            - possessive adjective and pronoun
himself        - reflexive

she            - subject
her            - object and possessive adjective
hers           - possessive pronoun
herself        - reflexive

it             - subject and object
its            - possessive adjective
itself         - reflexive
             - third person plural
they           - subject
them           - object
their          - possessive adjective
theirs         - possessive pronoun
themselves     - reflexive
             - other forms (demonstratives, interrogatives)
what
which
who
whom
this
that
these
those

           - VERB FORMS (using F.R. Palmer's nomenclature)
             - BE
am             - 1st person, present
is             - -s form (3rd person, present)
are            - present
was            - 1st person, past
were           - past
be             - infinitive
been           - past participle
being          - -ing form
             - HAVE
have           - simple
has            - -s form
had            - past
having         - -ing form
             - DO
do             - simple
does           - -s form
did            - past
doing          - -ing form
           - AUXILIARIES
             - WILL
will
would
             - SHALL
shall
should
             - CAN
can
could
             - MAY
may            - but not `might' because of its sensse of `power'
             - MUST
must           - `ought' is also a candidate for inclusion

           - ARTICLES
a
an
the

           - THE REST (Overlap among prepositions, conjunctions, adverbs etc is so high,
           - that classification is pointless.)
and
but
if
or
because
as
until
while

of
at
by
for
with
about
against
between
into
through
during
before
after
above
below
to
from
up
down
in
out
on
off
over
under

again
further
then
once

here
there
when
where
why
how

all
any
both
each
few
more
most
other
some
such

no
nor
not
only
own
same
so
than
too
very

